
  <sn><md>### Physical Properties of Soil Colloids

Since **shape, size, surface area, adsorption, and hydration** are all prominent characteristics of clays, they give rise to several **physical properties**.
These are surface-related phenomena that depend on the **amount and nature of interfaces** presented by soil colloids.

+++ Overview Table Physical Properties of Soil Colloids

| **Property**                       | **Description**                                               | **Main Cause / Influence**                         | **Effect on Soil**                    |
| ---------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| **Plasticity**                     | Ability of moist clay to be molded or shaped.                 | Plate-like structure, adsorbed water, cation type. | High plasticity → poor workability.   |
| **Cohesion**                       | Attraction between colloidal particles as moisture decreases. | Hydrogen bonding among clay surfaces and water.    | Increases soil compactness.           |
| **Swelling &amp; Shrinkage**           | Expansion and contraction with changing moisture.             | Water in layers and adsorbed ions.                 | Causes cracking and sealing behavior. |
| **Flocculation &amp; De-flocculation** | Aggregation or dispersion of colloidal particles.             | Type of adsorbed cations.                          | Determines soil structure stability.  |
+++
